<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transportation Strike Observed Despite Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Transportation Strike Observed Despite Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005153494 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1005153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Union Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The public transportation strike called to take 
place on Monday was observed throughtout the entire Caracas 
metropolitan area, even though the president of the Single Union 
of Independent Vehicles, the labor organization that convened 
the strike, reached an agreement at noon with the Transport and 
Communications Ministry on the payment of student subsidies. 
  Simon Ladera, president of the Single Union of Independent 
Vehicles, met with Transport Minister Cesar Quintini Rosales and 
reached an agreement, supposedly to end the strike, but the 
strike occurred anyway. 
  Ladera, after signing an agreement with the transport and 
communications minister stating that the public transportation 
sector would begin to charge the subsidized student bus fare 
rate starting this week, called on all labor union affiliates to 
return to work, but his request was not complied with. 
  Only buses operated on Monday afternoon. The subway operated 
with extra units. There were many pirate taxi cabs operating as 
well. The public transportation situation in Caracas and part 
of the interior of the country is expected to return to normal 
on Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

