<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violent Student Protests Reported for 4th Day </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Violent Student Protests Reported for 4th Day </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005195494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1811 GMT 10 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1005195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Caracas, 10 May (NOTIMEX) -- Violent student 
protests to demand the restoration of subsidized bus fare rates 
occurred for the fourth consecutive day today, police sources 
have reported. The protests on Monday were concentrated in the 
western part of Caracas, where groups of students seized at 
least two mass transit buses and clashed with riot police. It 
was unofficially reported that the young students, most of them 
high school students, set one of the vehicles on fire. 
  The disturbance, which spread to five areas west of the 
Venezuelan capital, is the most serious distubance reported so 
far in the government of Christian Democratic President Rafael 
Caldera, who took office last February. 
  The students, between the ages of 16 and 19, were also 
demanding punishment for those responsible for the murder of a 
fellow classmate. The student was shot three times by a 
policeman during the protests that took place in downtown 
Caracas. 
  On Monday, transportation sector workers went on strike to 
demand a 50-percent increase in bus fares and to protest the 
government's delay in the payment of student bus fare subsidies. 
  Similar protests resulted in the deaths of dozens of 
students 
during the administrations of social democrat Jaime Lusinchi 
(1984-89), Carlos Andres Perez (1989-93), and Ramon Velasquez 
(1993-94). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

