<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Evaluates Federal Police Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Evaluates Federal Police Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1105180594 Rio de Janeiro Rede Globo Television in 
Portuguese 1600 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1105180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro Rede Globo Television </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alexandre Garcia, from Brasilia] </F>
  [Text] President Itamar Franco has said that the objective 
of public service is to serve the people -- not to make the 
lives of the Brazilian people even more difficult. The final 
straw was yesterday's takeover of the public building that 
houses the Federal Police headquarters in Brasilia. 
  Strategic Affairs Secretary Mario Flores said that the Army 
was summoned because public disorder is unacceptable. The Army 
is using heavy weapons and equipment to discourage any 
resistance from the strikers, who were armed. Resistance might 
have serious consequences. 
  A short time ago, the president of the National Federation 
of 
Federal Policemen said the strikers will return their arms to 
the government to prove the peaceful nature of the strike. 
  The government claims the Army was summoned to guarantee 
constitutional rights and to prevent indiscipline, the taking 
over of public buildings, armed strikes, and to guarantee the 
right to work. 
  President Franco is now meeting with Army Minister Zenildo 
Zoroastro de Lucena and with Flores to evaluate the situation 
and its developments. 

</TEXT>

