<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Deploys Tanks in Brasilia; Coup Rumors `Persistent' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Deploys Tanks in Brasilia; Coup Rumors `Persistent' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1105204694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1910 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1105204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 11 May (EFE) -- The Brazilian Army today 
deployed several tanks and trucks in the administrative zone of 
Brasilia shortly after taking over the Federal Police [PF] 
headquarters in Brasilia and Sao Paulo, at the request of 
President Itamar Franco, to put an end to a 53-day police strike. 
  According to EFE reporters, after touring the Ministries 
Esplanade area -- where Planalto Palace, congressional 
buildings, and the Supreme Court building are located -- the 
military vehicles were parked in the vicinity of the cathedral. 
  A military deployment like today's has not taken place in 
Brasilia since the time of the military regime (1964-1985), when 
the Army used to deploy its tanks to intimidate government 
opponents. 
  The 7,000 PF personnel have been on strike to demand a 
salary 
increase, but their negotiations with the government have failed. 
  Union leader Jair Meneguelli -- president of the Sole 
Workers 
Center (CUT, leftist), to which the National Federation of 
Police Unions is affiliated -- has demanded that the government 
resume negotiations. 
  Meneguelli declined to comment on persistent rumors 
circulating in Brasilia that Franco, who last night ordered the 
military intervention in police headquarters, is promoting an 
institutional coup similar to the one engineered by Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori in 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-57041 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat092_m_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-092 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Insubordination Noted; Strike Leader Rejects Violence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Insubordination Noted; Strike Leader Rejects Violence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1105210494 Porto Alegre Radio Gaucha in Portuguese 2015 
GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1105210494 </F>
<F P=104>  Porto Alegre Radio Gaucha </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] High-ranking Army officers who are serving in the 
central barracks of Brasilia have been worrying all day about 
the adverse reaction of troops who refused to obey the orders of 
President Itamar Franco and Army Minister Zenildo Zoroastro de 
Lucena to intervene in the Federal Police [PF] strike. 
Commenting on the low PF salaries, an Army officer asked: How 
can we intervene in the PF strike if they are demanding the same 
rights that we have for some time been struggling for? 
  PF strike leader Francisco Carlos Garisto, who is an expert 
in drug enforcement and the president of the Federal Policemen 
National Federation, today commented on the Army's intervention 
in the strike. He rejected the possibility of clashes, but 
asserted that the PF will not give a single inch. 

</TEXT>

