<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Elena Gil] </F>
  [Text] Salvador de Bahia, Brazil, 12 May (PL) -- Cuban 
President Fidel Castro today concludes his brief visit to this 
city, where he made a service stop on his way to Havana 
following a trip to Barbados, Ghana, and South Africa. 
  Bahia Governor Antonio Embassagy welcomed Fidel Castro at 
the 
airport last night and hosted a dinner in Castro's honor. 
Dinner guests included Ramon Sanchez Parodi, Cuba's ambassador 
to Brazil; Former Bahia Governor Antonio Carlos De Magalhaes; 
Prefect Lidice Damata; and the Cuban delegation. 
  Magalhaes and Damata hosted Castro during his visit in 1993, 
when he attended the Third Ibero-American Summit. 
  Castro began his tour on 4 May in Barbados, where he 
attended 
the First World Conference on Sustainable Development of Small 
Island States, which was attended by 16 other heads of state and 
government. 
  From Barbados he traveled to South Africa to attend the 
inauguration of President Nelson Mandela. On his way to 
Pretoria, Castro made a stopover in Accra, the capital of Ghana, 
where he met with President Jerry John Rawlings. 
  Many statesmen and the accredited press showered Castro with 
attention in Pretoria and Bridgetown and asked him for private 
interviews. 
  Shortly before leaving Pretoria, the Cuban and South African 
foreign ministers reported that diplomatic relations were 
established between the two countries. 
  Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina; National Assembly 
President 
Ricardo Alarcon; Rosa Elena Simeon, minister of environment, 
science, and technology; and other officials accompanied Castro 
on this trip. 

</TEXT>

