<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panamanian President-Elect To Maintain Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panamanian President-Elect To Maintain Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005212394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1623 GMT 10 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1005212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Panama, 10 May (PL) -- Panamanian President-elect 
Ernesto Perez Balladares said on the night of 9 May that during 
his administration, Panama will maintain first-rate and 
respectful relations with Cuba. 
  Asked about the topic by journalists, Perez Balladares noted 
that relations with Cuba will be the same as those maintained 
with any other nation. Perez Balladares, a 47-year-old 
businessman, added that relations between the two nations will 
be characterized by respect for the systems prevailing in each 
country and noninterference in their respective internal affairs. 
  Panamanian-Cuban relations were virtually annulled following 
the U.S. invasion of Panama on 20 December 1989 and operate only 
at the level of acting charge d'affaires. 
  Perez Balladares, who will be proclaimed winner of the 8 May 
elections on 12 or 13 May, was nominated by the Democratic 
Revolutionary Party, which the U.S. military intervention 
removed from power. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-57091 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat093__a94023" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-093-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Official on Latin American Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Official on Latin American Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005164694 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1914 GMT 9 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1005164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 9 May (PL) -- Ernesto Melendez, minister 
president of the State Committee for Economic Cooperation, has 
said economic relations with Latin America have a promising 
future because of the great potential for developing trade, the 
sale of nontraditional products, and the assimilation of 
investment. 
  In an interview with TRABAJADORES, Melendez noted that Latin 
America is opening up to pharmaceutical and biotechnological 
products and medical equipment, which constitute new Cuban 
exports. 
  Melendez added that in terms of cooperation in the 
production 
sector, joint enterprises and associations linked to areas such 
as construction, textiles, energy, the mechanical industry, and 
services have been created. 
  Melendez labeled the process of joint economic activities 
with Mexico, Venezuela, Chile, Argentina, Brazil, and Ecuador as 
thriving, and he added that this process is expanding in the 
Caribbean through trade relations with the Dominican Republic, 
Jamaica, Guyana, and other nations. 
  Melendez emphasized the existence of a growing awareness of 
the Cuban situation; new legislation; good training of its 
workers, technicians, and professionals; and the efficient 
infrastructure created within the past 30 years. 
  In terms of economic integration with Latin America and the 
Caribbean, Melendez stressed that various models and free trade 
agreements among countries of the region are being considered. 
In this regard, Melendez said two aspects are being taken into 
account: the need to promote joint investigations for economic 
development and the understanding that this economic development 
must take place amid social equity. 
  Melendez concluded by saying that the documents of the 
Economic Commission for Latin America establish that more than 
200 million people out of the area's total population of 450 
million live in poverty, while the infant mortality rate is 57 
per every 1,000 live births. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

