<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sugar Industry Increases Production Efforts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sugar Industry Increases Production Efforts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1105000294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2044 GMT 9 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1105000294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 9 May (PL) -- Cuban sugar industry workers 
intensified their efforts to improve production levels of the 
current sugar harvest and to ensure a good harvest next year. 
  An official report released today announced that Havana 
Province will complete its production plans this Tuesday, thus 
becoming the first to achieve its goals in the country this year. 
  Havana Province leaders also said that they have planted 50 
percent of the lands assigned for next year's harvest and 
surpassed the historic records set for clearing sugar cane 
fields. 
  Candido Palmero, first secretary of the Communist Party of 
Cuba for the region, emphasized that these achievements were 
attained despite the difficult working conditions resulting from 
the lack of such vital resources as adequate clothing and foot 
ware and despite the cane workers' poor diets. 
  At this stage of the season, sugar workers are 
simultaneously 
doing cutting and grinding work as well as field cleaning and 
planting chores for next year's harvest. 
  Besides the progress achieved in Havana after 150 days of 
the 
harvest season, Ciego de Avila Province, in central Cuba, has 
reported the completion of its planting work. Granma, in the 
east, defied unfavorable weather conditions and set out to grind 
all the cane available. It will soon complete the spring 
planting phase. Rain and residual humidity are, in fact, two 
more obstacles to overcome for those brigades entrenched in the 
battle for higher yields. 
  While reviewing work progress in the field, Sugar Industry 
Minister Nelson Torres praised the determined attitude of the 
sugar workers. He underscored the need to harvest and grind all 
the available sugar cane in order to reach the planned sugar 
production volume. He suggested that the strategy is not to 
loose hope because of the rains and to keep the industry working 
at its potential, while looking at the harvest as a whole and 
doubling efforts. 
  According to reports released by the Sugar Ministry itself, 
the task also includes maintaining the cane planting process at 
the current pace, which is what will guarantee a better harvest 
next year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

