<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Gisela Bel Heredia] </F>
  [Text] Commander in Chief Fidel Castro arrived in the 
fatherland moments ago. Castro's trip began on 4 May in Barbados 
where he participated in the First Small Island States 
Conference on Sustainable Development. Fidel then traveled to 
Africa to attend [South African] President Nelson Mandela's 
inauguration. On a stopover in Ghana, Castro and his delegation 
met with Ghananian President Jerry Rawlings. In South Africa, 
Fidel met with dozens of people attending the inaugural in 
Pretoria. After the inauguration, Fidel met with Mandela and 
various people to discuss issues of bilateral interest. The next 
stop was Salvador, Brazil, where Castro met with the governor of 
Bahia State. The commander in chief's trip can be described as 
highly productive in view of the expressions of solidarity and 
affection toward Cuba he received at every stop. 
  The delegation accompanying Fidel included Rosa Elena 
Simeon, 
minister of science, technology, and the environment; and 
Politburo members Ricardo Alarcon de Quesada, president of the 
National Assembly of the People's Government, and Foreign 
Minister Roberto Robaina. 
  Commander in Chief Fidel Castro was greeted at Jose Marti 
International Airport by Army General Raul Castro, Politburo 
member Carlos Lage, and [Interior Minister] Abelardo Colome 
Ibarra. 

</TEXT>

