<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Ask Mexico for Compensation for NAFTA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Ask Mexico for Compensation for NAFTA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1305015494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0116 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1305015494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 11 May (EFE) -- Official sources reported 
here today that the Brazilian Government will ask Mexico for 
compensation for possible losses our country may sustain as a 
result of the tariff benefits Mexico will be granting to its 
NAFTA partners, the United States and Canada. 
  The Latin American Integration Association (ALADI) has 
decided that Mexico should compensate any of its 10 ALADI 
partners whose exports may be hurt by NAFTA. By compensating 
them, Mexico will be exempted from the ALADI requirement of 
sharing the benefits it may obtain through NAFTA with the other 
ALADI members. 
  To obtain a waiver for this requirement, Mexico will have to 
negotiate compensations with those ALADI members whose exports 
to Mexico may be hurt by NAFTA. 
  Arthur Denot Medeiros is the Brazilian Foreign Ministry 
under 
secretary for integration, economic affairs, and foreign trade. 
He said: "Waivers will be conditioned to compensatory 
negotiations." Denot added that this solution will contribute 
to preserving ALADI, "which has been institutionally weakened" 
since Mexico joined NAFTA. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

