<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1205232894 </F>
<F P=103> PA1205232894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
29 May 1994. 
  A recent poll conducted in 25 cities nationwide between 22 
and 26 April by the National Center shows Liberal Party 
presidential candidate Ernesto Samper leading Conservative Party 
candidate Andres Pastrana by 7 percent. In the case of a 
run-off election, Samper will reportedly beat out Pastrana by 53 
percent for Samper to 44 percent for Pastrana. During the 
closing of the Governors' Summit, candidate Pastrana stressed 
that the state cannot forget its responsibilities for the health 
of its citizens, and added that the tax base and revenue sources 
for the various departments must be broadened. (Santa Fe de 
Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 1 May 94 p 9A) 
  Pastrana's campaign-coordinator Luis Moreno has indicated 
Pastrana has always been willing to hold debates. Conservative 
vice presidential candidate Luis Ramirez said the latest polls 
indicate Pastrana is on the rise, people are very enthusiastic 
about Pastrana's campaign. He adds that, regardless of polls, 
they have always welcomed debates. Antonio Navarro Wolff, 
candidate for the 19 April Movement, noted that Samper's 
indecision regarding his participation in debates is worrisome. 
(Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal A Network in 
Spanish 0000 GMT 10 May 94) 

</TEXT>

