<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1205222594 </F>
<F P=103> PY1205222594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 12 May. 
  On 21 April, Education Minister Jorge Trelles Montero 
reported that the World Bank will grant a $270 million credit to 
the Education Ministry. The money will be used to finance 
teachers' training programs, and to build schools nationwide. 
(Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 22 Apr 94 Political Section p A2) 
  The Southern Peru Copper Corporation has purchased the ILO 
copper refinery for $65 million. Company President Charles 
Preble said they will invest $20.2 million in modernizing the 
plant in the upcoming three years. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in 
Spanish 23 Apr 94 p 9) 
  On 28 April, Energy and Mines Minister Daniel Hokama 
Tokashiki confirmed that foreign companies will invest more than 
$300 million in oil exploitation in several parts of the 
country, especially in the Talara zone, Piura Department. He 
noted that oil reserves had increased 10 percent, and that 
production rose from 105,000 to 130,000 barrels of oil per day. 
He also reported that the Newton Mining Corporation will invest 
$50 million this year in the exploitation of the second gold 
reserve in the Maqui Maqui zone, in Cajamarca Department. (Lima 
EL PERUANO in Spanish 29 Apr 94 p A2) 
  The Fisheries Ministry reported that fish meal exports 
expanded from 88 million metric tons in February 1993 to 355 
million metric tons in February 1994, while frozen fish exports 
increased from 600,000 metric tons to almost 3 million metric 
tons during the same period. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 2 May p 
A22) 
  The National Statistics Institute, INEI, reported that the 
April inflation rate was 1.5 percent, while the cumulated 
inflation rate was 7.7 percent for the year's first four months 
and 27.9 percent from May 1993 to April 1994. INEI Director 
Felix Murillo said the April inflation rate was one of the 
lowest since December 1977. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 3 May 
94 p 6) 
  INEI reported that domestic production grew 8.6 percent in 
the year's first quarter. Construction registered the highest 
increase with 27.7 percent; fishing 27.1 percent; mining 3.2 
percent; manufactured products 10.5 percent; and agriculture and 
livestock 8.9 percent. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 4 May 94 p 
B12) 

</TEXT>

