<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1205143794 </F>
<F P=103> PY1205143794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 12 May: 
  The National Statistics Institute, INE, has reported that 
the 
average income of Montevideo households increased 11 percent in 
real terms in the first quarter of 1994 compared with the 
corresponding period last year. It totals 5,215 pesos ($1,144) 
free of rent. The ceiling for the lower income bracket was 
2,713 pesos ($595) while the floor for the higher income bracket 
was 8,515 ($1,868). The INE further reported that salaries in 
the private sector grew 1.8 percent in real terms in March while 
those in the public sector declined 1.6 percent in the same 
period. The average wage index grew 9.9 percent in the first 
quarter, representing a 1.9 percent increase in real terms. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 28 Apr 94 p 10) 
  The Central Bank disclosed on 29 April that wholesale prices 
rose 1 percent in April, which represents a 32.1 percent 
increase over the last 12 months. The upward trend of the 
wholesale price index continued in the first quarter of the 
year, increasing 8.2 percent compared with 7.4 percent in the 
corresponding period last year. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR 
ECONOMICO in Spanish 2 May 94 p 9) 

</TEXT>

