<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaviria: Ruling on Drug Use Not To Affect Struggle </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gaviria: Ruling on Drug Use Not To Affect Struggle </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1205190294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1742 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1205190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sandra Vergara from the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] President Cesar Gaviria has not regressed regarding 
the elimination of sanctions for personal drug use. Today, he 
warned the ruling of the Constitutional Court does not affect 
the struggle against drug trafficking. 
  Today, the president of the republic, speaking at the 
General 
Santander National Police Academy, made categorical remarks on 
the elimination of sanctions for personal drug use. He said he 
does not agree with this decision because several fundamental 
rights are at stake, including the right to security and 
tranquillity of Colombians. 
  [Begin Gaviria recording in progress] ...who believe that 
the 
interpretation of Article 16 of our Constitution, which contains 
the right to personal independence, cannot be taken to extremes 
bringing us to an individualistic society. In this case, 
various rights come into conflict and the Court should have 
pondered the value of each right, should have tried to reconcile 
them, and should not have disregarded the rights to security, 
health, and tranquillity of Colombians. 
  The government believes that carrying and consuming drugs 
for 
personal use should continue to be prohibited. [end recording] 
  The president of the Republic concluded that severe 
restrictions will be adopted so that drug consumption will not 
take place in public places, schools, or universities, or so 
that drugs will not be consumed by minors, pregnant women, or by 
people doing jobs involving dangerous activities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

