<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1205202294 </F>
<F P=103> PA1205202294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
21 August. 
  During a telephone interview, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, 
presidential candidate for the Party of the Democratic 
Revolution (PRD), admitted that the Mexico City branch of the 
PRD had engaged in irregularities in nominating its candidates 
to the Assembly of Representatives of the Federal District. He 
urged those involved to respect the party's mandates, and he 
said the mistakes could be corrected. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in 
Spanish 5 May 94 pp 1, 6) 
  Dr. Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon, presidential candidate 
for 
the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), visited Chiapas 
State for the second time today. Dr. Zedillo visited the town 
of Tapachula, where he told those present that he wants the 
peace agreements with the Zapatist National Liberation Army to 
be signed to enable them to be fulfilled as soon as possible. 
Zedillo said it is "unacceptable" to have so many poor people 
in such a rich state. "We have to achieve social justice here," 
according to Zedillo. (Mexico City Radio ACIR in Spanish 0000 
GMT 6 May 94) 
  PRI candidate Ernesto Zedillo has met with representatives 
of 
the National Network of Handicapped People in southern Mexico 
City. The representatives denounced the lack of opportunities 
for the handicapped in the areas of education and employment. 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 11 May 
94) 
  The National Action Party (PAN) has asked the other eight 
political parties that will take part in the August elections to 
allow public audits of their campaign expenses, according to 
Felipe Calderon, secretary general of the National Executive 
Committee of the PAN. Calderon said the audits would serve to 
clear doubts over the campaign expenses of the PRI, which had 
reported expenditures of 24.515 million pesos as of 17 March. 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 11 May 
94) 

</TEXT>

