<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Confirms `Neutral' Stance Regarding Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Confirms `Neutral' Stance Regarding Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1305232994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1708 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1305232994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 12 May (EFE) -- Political sources have 
reported here today that the U.S. Government has asserted to 
Brazilian Socialist presidential candidate Luis Inacio "Lula" da 
Silva this week in Washington that it will remain neutral 
regarding the 3 October general elections to be held in Brazil. 
  Workers Party (PT) leader Lula da Silva, 48, is the favorite 
in the upcoming presidential elections. 
  After meeting Alexander Watson, the U.S. assistant secretary 
of state for inter-American affairs, in Washington on 11 May, Da 
Silva said: "It is very important that a country such as the 
United States maintain the impartial position President Bill 
Clinton has been postulating regarding the Brazilian elections." 
  The Socialist presidential candidate will return to Brazil 
today, after a five-day visit to Washington, New York, and 
Boston. During the trip he met officials of the U.S. executive 
branch and Congress, and gave several lectures at Harvard and 
other universities. 
  Da Silva told Watson that he opposes the U.S. embargo 
against 
Cuba because it punishes the Cuban people. He added that he 
also opposes the choice of Miami -- where most anti-Castro 
Cubans live -- as the venue for the summit of American chiefs of 
state convened by Bill Clinton for 9 and 10 December. 
  The PT leader has defended the idea that Cuban President 
Fidel Castro, who has not been invited, should participate in 
the summit. 

</TEXT>

