<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canadian Trade Official Favors Chilean NAFTA Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canadian Trade Official Favors Chilean NAFTA Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1305221994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1447 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1305221994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, 13 May (EFE) -- Allen Kilpatrick, Canadian 
international trade vice minister, said here today that he 
firmly supports Chile's entry into NAFTA. 
  Today Kilpatrick participated in the signing of a $20 
million 
loan agreement that will be used to finance the purchasing of 
equipment for the new Panque Hydroelectric Power Plant that is 
being built in southern Chile. 
  The Canadian official stressed that in his government's 
opinion "there are no inadequacies whatsoever" preventing 
Chile's incorporation into NAFTA, and that Ottawa has officially 
communicated its favorable stance to Santiago. 
  Initial reports indicate that Chile's incorporation could be 
"relatively quick" because only a few changes "of little 
importance" would be necessary, Kilpatrick added. 
  The minister said Canadian participation in NAFTA was 
positive, adding that even though the agreement was extended to 
include Mexico in January 1994, trade between the two countries 
had already started to increase. 
  Allen Kilpatrick emphasized the importance of Canadian 
investments in Chile, which total $3 billion and are mainly 
concentrated in the mining area. Kilpatrick added that current 
studies contemplate additional investments of $1 billion in 
Chile. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

