<H3> <TI>   Army Troops Still Occupying Police Buildings in Sao Paulo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Troops Still Occupying Police Buildings in Sao Paulo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1705005694 Rio de Janeiro Rede Globo Television in 
Portuguese 2300 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1705005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro Rede Globo Television </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Army troops have withdrawn from Federal Police [PF] 
buildings in Porto Alegre and Foz do Iguacu, but they are still 
occupying PF facilities in Sao Paulo. 
  The order to withdraw from Foz do Iguacu came late in the 
afternoon. The 180 Army soldiers who have been guarding the 
Brazilian border with Paraguay for the past four days quickly 
boarded their trucks and returned to barracks. 
  Army troops are still occupying the three PF buildings in 
Sao 
Paulo. Traffic remains closed and pedestrians have only limited 
access to the area. Army sentries continue to monitor the area 
from the roof of the main building. 
  Although Planalto Palace authorized the withdrawal of 
troops, 
the Army will not withdraw in Sao Paulo until it becomes certain 
that the PF strikers will resume basic services. The Army 
southeast regional commander will decide when to withdraw the 
troops. 
  Complying with orders from President Itamar Franco, Justice 
Minister Alexandre Dupeyrat will meet again tomorrow morning 
with members of the Chamber of Deputies National Defense 
Committee in an attempt to resume negotiations and end the PF 
strike. 

</TEXT>

