<H3> <TI>   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Meets Local Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Agriculture Secretary Meets Local Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1705003594 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2122 GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1705003594 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Buenos Aires, 16 May (NA) -- [Passage omitted] 
[U.S. Agriculture Secretary Mike] Espy held a news conference 
with Felipe Sola, his Argentine colleague, at the Economy 
Ministry after meeting with Economy Vice Minister Carlos Sanchez. 
  The U.S. official arrived on 13 May (his visit is part of a 
trip that will take him to Brazil on 17 May and finally to 
Mexico). He also met with President Carlos Menem, Vice Foreign 
Minister Fernando Petrella, and with the Senate and Chamber of 
Deputies Agriculture Committees. 
  Espy and Sola termed their talks as "excellent and 
fruitful." 
The Argentine official insisted on the global need to eradicate 
dumping [preceding word in English] and subsidies. 
  "I told Espy that maintaining our share of the Brazilian 
market is our main concern," said Sola, adding: "We asked for 
political priority in sanitary and phyto-sanitary [sanitarios y 
fitosanitarios] fields." 
  Sola indicated that on 6 June a "high level" U.S. delegation 
will visit the country to study the phyto-sanitary situation and 
the conclusions of this delegation will be decisive in the 
purchase of Argentine beef by the United States. [sentence as 
received] [passage omitted] 
  Espy's remarks have a political interpretation because 
Argentina currently maintains a strong tug-of-war with the 
United States over the Pharmaceutical Patents Law. On several 
occasions, U.S. Ambassador James Cheek has supported a solomonic 
decision: Patents for subsidies. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

