<H3> <TI>   Ex-De Facto President Receives 10-Day Sentence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ex-De Facto President Receives 10-Day Sentence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1605221994 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 16 
May 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PY1605221994 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] (NA) -- Former de facto president, retired General 
Alejandro Lanusse was sentenced to 10 days arrest by the Army 
over the weekend for publicly criticizing the government, 
unofficial sources said yesterday [15 May]. 
  A local news agency reported that Lanusse has been under 
arrest at the Military Hospital since Saturday [14 May]. Army 
Chief-of-Staff Lieutenant General Martin Balza ordered Lanusse's 
detention, which will extend until May 25, said the sources. 
  Lanusse asserted last week during a cable television 
programme that the governments of former General Juan Peron and 
the current Justicialist administration were "the most corrupt" 
he had known. 
  The retired general--who headed a three-man ruling junta 
from 
1971 to 1973--also said that Balza should not have taken a 
personal interest in the alleged murder of recruit Omar Carrasco 
at a military base in Neuquen. His opinions are said to have 
been taken into account by the Army's top brass in ordering the 
arrest. 

</TEXT>

